<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SECTION 4: OWNER KEY -->
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s-security">
<div class="stag">Security Architecture</div>
<div class="sh">The Owner Key System</div>
<div class="sp">A published SOP is a promise. It can't be quietly changed by anyone — not a disgruntled employee, not an overeager manager, not even the AI. Only the Owner Key unlocks modifications.</div>

<div class="key-visual">
<div class="key-icon">🔐</div>
<div class="key-content">
<h3>The Owner Key Concept</h3>
<p>Think of it like the master key to a safe deposit box at a bank. The bank employees can see the boxes exist. They can even describe what's inside. But only the key holder can open, add, remove, or change the contents. In this system, published SOPs are the safe deposit boxes. The Owner Key is the only way to modify them.</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="sh" style="font-size:18px;margin-top:20px">Permission Model</div>

<div class="permission-grid">
<div class="perm-card owner">
<h4>🔑 Owner (Key Holder)</h4>
<p>Publish SOPs, modify published content, approve changes, delegate temporary keys, view full audit trail, configure security settings, delete content permanently.</p>
</div>
<div class="perm-card manager">
<h4>📋 Manager</h4>
<p>Create drafts, submit for publication, request modifications to published SOPs (goes to approval queue), run turnover assessments, view team SOPs, create brainstorm sessions.</p>
</div>
<div class="perm-card staff">
<h4>👤 Staff</h4>
<p>View published SOPs for their role, ask AI questions, suggest edits (routed to manager), mark SOPs as "needs update" with reason, add comments and context.</p>
</div>
<div class="perm-card readonly">
<h4>👁️ Read-Only / New Hire</h4>
<p>View published SOPs for their role only, complete onboarding checklists, ask AI questions, cannot suggest edits until training period complete.</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="sh" style="font-size:18px;margin-top:20px">Modification Workflow</div>

<div class="flow">
<div class="flow-node">📝 Change<br>Requested</div>
<div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
<div class="flow-node">📬 Enters<br>Approval Queue</div>
<div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
<div class="flow-node">👁️ Owner<br>Reviews Diff</div>
<div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
<div class="flow-node highlight">🔑 Owner Key<br>Applied</div>
<div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
<div class="flow-node security">✅ New Version<br>Published</div>
</div>

<div class="callout green"><strong>What the audit trail captures:</strong> WHO requested the change, WHAT changed (exact diff), WHEN it was approved, WHO approved it (which key), and WHY (required reason field). Every version is preserved. Nothing is ever truly deleted — old versions are archived, not overwritten.</div>

<div class="grid-2">
<div class="card">
<div class="card-h">🔑 MVP: Owner Key in Notion</div>
<div class="card-p">In the Notion MVP, the Owner Key is implemented through Notion's permission system enhanced with workflow automation:</div>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Mechanism</th><th>How</th></tr>
<tr><td>Publish Lock</td><td>A checkbox property only the Owner can toggle (Notion page-level locks)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Approval Queue</td><td>A separate database where change requests live until Owner reviews</td></tr>
<tr><td>Version History</td><td>Notion's built-in page history + a manual Version # property</td></tr>
<tr><td>Audit Trail</td><td>A linked database that auto-logs every status change with timestamp and user</td></tr>
<tr><td>Role Permissions</td><td>Notion teamspace permissions: Owner = full, Manager = edit drafts, Staff = comment only on published</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
<div class="card">
<div class="card-h">🔐 Production: Cryptographic Owner Key</div>
<div class="card-p">When the product moves to production, the Owner Key becomes a real cryptographic system:</div>
<table class="tbl">
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Implementation</th></tr>
<tr><td>Key Generation</td><td>Unique cryptographic key generated at account creation, stored in hardware security module (HSM)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Two-Factor Publish</td><td>Owner Key + biometric or authenticator app to publish/modify</td></tr>
<tr><td>Delegation Tokens</td><td>Owner can create time-limited, scope-limited tokens for managers (e.g., "edit billing SOPs for 24 hours")</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tamper Evidence</td><td>Blockchain-style hash chain — every published SOP's hash depends on the previous one. Any tampering breaks the chain.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Emergency Access</td><td>Break-glass protocol: if Owner is unavailable, a pre-configured recovery process (not a backdoor) allows access with full audit logging</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
</section>

